LBB Unsupervised Learning

Francis Yeh

1 Introduction

1.1 Background

Imagine you are employed at a particular conglomerate distributing FMCG goods through a distribution network consisting of hotel, restaurant, cafes and all variety of retail outlets. Our CRM system collected the annual spending in each of the product category for each of the customer grouping ie,Horeca and Retail and we would like to apply Unsupervised Learning algorithms, namely

  1. Dimensionality Reduction (using PCA)
  2. Clustering (using k-means clustering)

to potentially help the conglomerate in their customer segmentation (beyond the existing customer grouping(channel) and region), sales group assignment and/or campaign execution.

1.2 Data Source

The dataset consists of 440 observations and 8 variables. https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Wholesale+customers

1.2.1 Overview of Variables

  1. CHANNEL: customer classification
    • 1 = Horeca (Hotel/Restaurant/Cafe) or
    • 2 = Retail
  2. REGION: customers Region (1 = Lisnon, 2 = Oporto or 3 = Others)
  3. FRESH: annual spending (m.u) on fresh products (Continuous);
  4. MILK: annual spending (m.u) on milk products (Continuous);
  5. GROCERY: annual spending (m.u)on grocery products (Continuous);
  6. FROZEN: annual spending (m.u)on frozen products (Continuous)
  7. DETERGENTS_PAPER: annual spending (m.u) on detergents and paper products (Continuous)
  8. DELICATESSEN: annual spending (m.u)on and delicatessen products (Continuous);

1.3 Libraries and Setup

To run the data preparation and the statistical analysis, the following libraries are loaded

1.3.1 Within Sum of Squares

wss <- function(data, maxCluster = 9) {
    # Initialize within sum of squares
    SSw <- (nrow(data) - 1) * sum(apply(data, 2, var))
    SSw <- vector()
    for (i in 2:maxCluster) {
        SSw[i] <- sum(kmeans(data, centers = i)$withinss)
    }
    plot(1:maxCluster, SSw, type = "o", xlab = "Number of Clusters", ylab = "Within groups sum of squares", pch=19)
}

Interestingly, using FactoMineR package,one can get a much more detailed output when performing the PCA. Dimension/Component 1 contributes to 44.08% of the variance followed by 28.38% for Dimension / Component 2.In order to explain 80% or greater of the variation, the first 3 components(PC) will be sufficient to explain the variances.

We can see that the Dim. 1, Dim. 2, and Dim. 3 have very little correlation.

5 k-means Clustering

Here, we decide to start with k= 3 since we have existing “Channel” variable in our data which comprises 2 “clusters” ie. Horeca and Retail.

set.seed = 10
library(factoextra)
wholesalekm_res <- kmeans(wholesale1, centers = 3, nstart = 25)

The output of Kmeans returns a list of components. The most important one are listed below:

cluster: A vector of integers (from 1:k) indicating the cluster to which each point is allocated.

centers: A matrix of cluster centers.

totss: The total sum of squares.

withinss: Vector of within-cluster sum of squares, one component per cluster. tot.withinss: Total within-cluster sum of squares, i.e. sum(withinss).

betweenss: The between-cluster sum of squares, i.e. \(totss-tot.withinss\). size: The number of points in each cluster.

5.1 Within Sum of Squares

wss(wholesale1)

6 Summary

After breaking down the clusters to 3, let see how the business may benefit from the clustering. We can generalise the clusters as below:

Cluster 1 (size 60) - Relatively higher proportion of purchase ( in term of DM) in Frozen, Fresh, Delicassen (as compared to Grocery, Milk, Detergents_Paper) from mostly the Horeca channel

Cluster 2 (size 50) - Relatively higher proportion of purchase (in term of DM) in Grocery, Milk, Detergents_Paper categories (as compared to Frozen, Fresh, Delicassen) from mostly the Retail channel

Cluster 3 (size 330) - Remaining (outside of both Clusters 1 and 2)

Application: Business could decide if the above clustering could be used in scenarios such as target group selection for campaign execution.

Further iterations of the clustering maybe necessary if business requires clear segregation in term of Horeca and Retail or decide the no of clusters potentially needed based on some optimal cluster size.
